sec.p:
Malondialdehyde (MDA), a marker of lipid peroxidation, was quantified using a thiobarbituric acid (TBA) reactive substances assay, as described by Lykkesfeldt27. In this method, TBA reacts with MDA in an acidic medium at 95 °C for 30 min to produce a pink chromogen measurable at 534 nm. Briefly, the reaction mixture was incubated, and the absorbance of each sample (A sample) was measured at 534 nm against a reagent blank using a UNICO UV-2100 spectrophotometer. The absorbance of the standard (A standard) was measured against distilled water. The concentration of MDA in serum was calculated using the following formula:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\text{M}\text{D}\text{A}\:({\upmu\:}\text{m}\text{o}\text{l}/\text{m}\text{L})=\frac{\text{A}\:\text{s}\text{a}\text{m}\text{p}\text{l}\text{e}}{\text{A}\:\text{s}\text{t}\text{a}\text{n}\text{d}\text{a}\text{r}\text{d}\:}\times\:10$$\end{document}

SOD activity was assessed using the method of Marklund and Marklund28, which is based on the enzyme’s ability to inhibit the phenazine methosulfate (PMS)-mediated reduction of nitroblue tetrazolium (NBT). Absorbance was measured at 560 nm over a period of 5 min at 25 °C using the UNICO UV-2100 spectrophotometer. The percentage inhibition of NBT reduction by SOD was calculated as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\mathbf{\%}\text{I}\text{n}\text{h}\text{i}\text{b}\text{i}\text{t}\text{i}\text{o}\text{n}=\frac{{\Delta\:}\text{A}\:\text{c}\text{o}\text{n}\text{t}\text{r}\text{o}\text{l}-{\Delta\:}\text{A}\:\text{s}\text{a}\text{m}\text{p}\text{l}\text{e}}{{\Delta\:}\text{A}\:\text{c}\text{o}\text{n}\text{t}\text{r}\text{o}\text{l}}\times\:100$$\end{document}

